1
00:00:29.233 --> 00:00:40.433
In the last video, in the “First-Row Superposition Method”, some viewers still had questions about the row-by-row relation between buttons and lights. This time we will explain clearly where this relation formula comes from.

2
00:00:40.433 --> 00:00:47.533
We use B for buttons, L for lights, ⊕ (plus) for superposition, and ¬ (NOT) for flip.

3
00:00:47.533 --> 00:00:57.233
n means the n-th row (top to bottom) of buttons or lights. Because we derive row by row, n also means the n-th derivation step.

4
00:00:57.233 --> 00:01:08.933
x means the x-th column (left to right) of buttons. We write each light as a superposition of some columns’ buttons in the first row. Here x is not only for the first row.

5
00:01:08.933 --> 00:01:18.733
y means the y-th column (left to right) of lights. The formula works for any y-th light, so we omit y.

6
00:01:18.733 --> 00:01:26.533
Here, pink dots mean “use buttons to represent buttons”, and light-blue squares mean “use buttons to represent lights”.

7
00:01:26.533 --> 00:01:38.433
In the last video, because the final goal is to represent lights by buttons, we omitted “buttons represent buttons”, so the pink dots directly mean “buttons represent lights”.

8
00:01:38.433 --> 00:01:46.633
Let’s use a concrete example. In a 5×5 grid, we number buttons and lights as 1—25.

9
00:01:46.633 --> 00:01:59.733
In the “Superposition Method”, we represent each light as a superposition of all buttons. For example: L1=B1⊕B2⊕B6, L6=B1⊕B6⊕B7⊕B11.

10
00:01:59.733 --> 00:02:12.933
With this, we get a linear system with 25 unknowns. We write it as an augmented matrix: the button matrix and the flip vector, that is, the light vector.

11
00:02:12.933 --> 00:02:19.367
In the “First-Row Superposition Method”, we need to represent lights as a superposition of the first row’s buttons.

12
00:02:19.367 --> 00:02:25.967
These five matrices each mean: for column y, which first-row buttons are added together.

13
00:02:25.967 --> 00:02:39.167
Because pressing is dynamic, before we press row 2, we have L1=B1⊕B2, meaning light L1 is the superposition of B1 and B2 in row 1.

14
00:02:39.167 --> 00:02:53.867
Then, B6=¬L1=¬(B1⊕B2), meaning button B6 is the flip of light L1. So row-2 button B6 and row-1 light L1 have the same superposition state.

15
00:02:53.867 --> 00:03:03.567
The only difference is: B6 is the flipped version of L1. The flip vector beside it shows whether a button or light is flipped.

16
00:03:03.567 --> 00:03:14.167
For example, when the first light L1 in the first vector is on, it means L1 needs an extra flip, besides the button superposition we just said.

17
00:03:14.167 --> 00:03:30.167
Similarly, B7=¬L2=¬(B1⊕B2⊕B3), so button B7 is the flip of light L2. Again, row-2 button B7 and row-1 light L2 have the same superposition state.

18
00:03:30.167 --> 00:03:39.067
Here we complete the state of button B1: when we write B1 using first-row buttons, we have B1=B1.

19
00:03:39.067 --> 00:03:51.867
Next, look at light L6. L6=B1⊕B6⊕B7=B1⊕¬(B1⊕B2)⊕¬(B1⊕B2⊕B3)=B1⊕B3.

20
00:03:51.867 --> 00:04:05.467
Another example: L7=B2⊕B6⊕B7⊕B8=B2⊕¬(B1⊕B2)⊕¬(B1⊕B2⊕B3)⊕¬(B2⊕B3⊕B4)=¬B4.

21
00:04:05.467 --> 00:04:16.400
By continuing this derivation, we can represent any L as a superposition of B1—B5. After adding the flip part, we get the full matrix.

22
00:04:16.400 --> 00:04:29.867
Now, if we write index 1—25 as coordinates x,y, then buttons and lights can be written as the formulas above. Let’s take L7(2)=L(2,2,2) as an example.

23
00:04:29.867 --> 00:04:36.967
Here our matrices also satisfy another property. We call it the “cross even-check rule”.

24
00:04:36.967 --> 00:04:45.367
For one element, add the element at the same spot in the left and right matrices, and also add the left and right neighbor elements in the current matrix, and you get zero.

25
00:04:45.367 --> 00:04:53.167
This is the property in the last video, in the “Optimized Matrix Generation” part, and we will prove it later.

26
00:04:53.167 --> 00:05:02.167
With this property, the relation formula can be changed to use only the current matrix’s elements, and no longer depends on the left and right matrices.

27
00:05:02.167 --> 00:05:11.567
So we can remove y from the formula. Then each light can be written as the superposition of the upper-left, upper, upper-right, and itself (left/middle/right) buttons in the current matrix.

28
00:05:11.567 --> 00:05:21.267
Also, the next row’s buttons are the flip of the previous row’s lights, and the next row’s lights are the superposition of flips of the upper-left, upper, upper-right, and itself lights.

29
00:05:21.267 --> 00:05:27.367
So if we take out the flip ¬, we get the formula we derived at the start.

30
00:05:27.367 --> 00:05:39.267
That is: buttons are the superposition of the previous row’s left/middle/right buttons and the row-before-previous buttons. And lights are the superposition of the previous row’s left/middle/right buttons and the row-before-previous lights.

31
00:05:39.267 --> 00:05:48.367
You can see the button and light relation formulas have the same shape, because the previous row’s lights are exactly the next row’s buttons.

32
00:05:48.367 --> 00:05:59.567
Because we finally need lights, we derive 5 rows of lights from the first row of buttons. Because the last derivation is lights, buttons also have 5 rows.

33
00:05:59.567 --> 00:06:06.667
For the flip part, we can list it separately and derive it in a similar way, and write it as formula Y.

34
00:06:06.667 --> 00:06:13.267
That is: the next row’s flip is the flip of (previous row’s left/middle/right plus row-before-previous) superposition.

35
00:06:13.267 --> 00:06:25.367
You can see formula Y is like formula B. The difference is: Y starts from the zero vector, and we cannot drop the flip sign ¬.

36
00:06:25.367 --> 00:06:37.467
1. Use the zero vector: the first flip happens when we derive from row 1 to row 2. Before that, there is no flip, so Y’s first row is all zeros.

37
00:06:37.467 --> 00:06:50.067
2. The flip sign ¬ must stay: each derivation step needs a flip, so we cannot omit it. In the earlier formula we pulled the flip out, so we didn’t need ¬ there.

38
00:06:50.067 --> 00:07:03.700
3. Use y instead of x: the flip part is pulled out from the flips of all previous buttons, so it represents flips of lights, not flips of one button.

39
00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:09.800
In fact, the button matrix can also be derived in another, more direct way.

40
00:07:09.800 --> 00:07:19.800
First, in the first matrix, we press the first button in row 1. Then press row-2 buttons to remove as many row-1 lights as possible.

41
00:07:19.800 --> 00:07:27.200
Then press row-3 buttons to remove row-2 lights. Keep doing this until the last row.

42
00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:34.400
In the end, the last row’s button and light states match the matrix we derived before.

43
00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:44.600
Likewise, in the second matrix, press the second button in row 1, then derive downward, and we get the last row’s button and light states for the second matrix.

44
00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:52.033
With this method, we can get the last row states for all matrices.

45
00:07:52.033 --> 00:07:57.133
Also, the flip vector can be derived in a similar way.

46
00:07:57.133 --> 00:08:07.167
We turn on all lights, then use the same method to try to remove all lights, and we can also get the last row state of the flip vector.

47
00:08:07.167 --> 00:08:21.167
We call this the “remainder matrix method”. It is essentially the same as the first-row superposition method, and you can prove it if you like.

48
00:08:21.167 --> 00:08:34.600
In the “Generate Optimized Matrix” part, we reorder the matrix rows. This actually swaps n and y, so the y-th matrix (left to right) becomes the n-th matrix.

49
00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:44.500
These n matrices all satisfy the cross even-check rule: add the up/down/left/right four cells and get zero, so we omit n in the formula.

50
00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:52.300
This is the same as before, only n and y are swapped, so positions change.

51
00:08:52.300 --> 00:08:59.900
This is a very important property. With it, we can derive later lights from the first light.

52
00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:07.000
In the later O(n²) algorithm, the core optimization is also based on this property.

53
00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.100
Now let’s use math induction to prove this property.

54
00:09:12.100 --> 00:09:20.300
Because the button matrix on the right is the same as the light matrix on the left, for simplicity we only look at the button matrix.

55
00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:31.000
First, assume the previous two matrices B(n-1) and B(n-2) satisfy this property. Now we prove B(n) also satisfies it.

56
00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:36.400
Add parameter y to the relation and rewrite it.

57
00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:43.600
For B(n), we write the expression vertically as four terms, then plug the relation into it.

58
00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:55.200
After plugging in, we get 16 terms. Now reorder the terms, swap y and n, like the swap in the “Optimized Matrix Generation” part.

59
00:09:55.200 --> 00:10:09.700
It is easy to see these four terms belong to B(n-1) or B(n-2), and their element relations satisfy the cross even-check rule, so the whole expression becomes zero.

60
00:10:09.700 --> 00:10:20.300
Now we only need to prove the leftmost two matrices also satisfy this property. The first matrix is the identity matrix, so it clearly satisfies it.

61
00:10:20.300 --> 00:10:30.400
The second matrix can be written as the superposition of the two matrices to its left. Since the identity matrix has no matrix on its left, it is like adding a zero matrix.

62
00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:37.500
The zero matrix clearly satisfies the property, so the second matrix also satisfies it.

63
00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:53.000
Because B(n) has this property, we only need the first row of B(n), then we can use the formula to derive the later rows and get the full matrix B(n).

64
00:10:53.000 --> 00:11:05.067
To make an O(n²) algorithm, we also need a similar idea: avoid working on the whole matrix, and use the first row to find an inverse or a solution.

65
00:11:05.067 --> 00:11:17.433
Take n=7 as an example. Here B is the button matrix B(n) we talked about, and y is the last row of the flip vector, i.e. the augmented vector of B(n).

66
00:11:17.433 --> 00:11:26.367
Our goal is: for Bx=y, given B’s first row and y, find x.

67
00:11:26.367 --> 00:11:33.600
If we put together the first rows of B for different n, the matrix looks like this, call it B'.

68
00:11:33.600 --> 00:11:43.800
Note: this B' is not the full matrix B for a fixed n, but the result of stacking the first rows of B(n).

69
00:11:43.800 --> 00:11:58.533
Also, here we start from n=0 and derive n times. The last “1” is not included in the first row of matrix B. For example when n=7, the first row is 1011011, and we omit the last 1.

70
00:11:58.533 --> 00:12:03.367
The rewritten matrix is B''=B'⊕I.

71
00:12:03.367 --> 00:12:08.533
If we stack the first rows of Y, it looks like this, call it Y'.

72
00:12:08.533 --> 00:12:15.633
After merging, Y' has the relation formula above.

73
00:12:15.633 --> 00:12:27.167
To avoid operating on the whole matrix, we need to factor matrix B. Here we introduce an important matrix H, called the adjacency diffusion matrix.

74
00:12:27.167 --> 00:12:41.200
For each element of H, if x and y differ by 1, it is 1, otherwise it is 0. If we multiply a vector v by H, it is the same as spreading each element of v to left and right, then adding them.

75
00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:47.367
This is because each row of the matrix is exactly the left-right spread result of one element of the vector.

76
00:12:47.367 --> 00:12:55.167
It is easy to see: each matrix B in the “First-Row Superposition Method” can be written using H as the formula above.

77
00:12:55.167 --> 00:13:02.067
Here, B(0), B(1), B(2) are written as different superpositions of powers of H.

78
00:13:02.067 --> 00:13:14.200
If we write the coefficients of these H terms as a polynomial c(n,x), we get a relation formula similar to matrix B. Also, write these coefficients as a matrix, call it C.

79
00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:25.633
Note: multiplying by H in the coefficients means shifting right, not left-right spreading, so the expression has x-1 but not x+1.

80
00:13:25.633 --> 00:13:36.167
Now, if we multiply H many times, that is Hⁿ, and stack the first rows Hⁿ(0), it looks like this.

81
00:13:36.167 --> 00:13:46.767
We call this lower-triangular matrix K, also called the Krylov matrix or diffusion basis matrix. For the n-th row of K, we have the formula above.

82
00:13:46.767 --> 00:13:59.100
Here each next row is the previous row times H, that is, the left-right spread of the previous row. So for each element in K, we have the relation formula above.

83
00:13:59.100 --> 00:14:07.000
Now we define a polynomial p(x). Our goal is to break B into powers of Hⁿ.

84
00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:14.400
Put matrix H into polynomial p(x), get p(H), and use it to represent matrix B.

85
00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:21.300
Then the original problem Bx=y becomes p(H)x=y.

86
00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:30.200
Now we need to compute the coefficients of polynomial p(H). We call the coefficient vector p.

87
00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:42.133
To simplify, we only care about the first row B(0), call it b. By the definition of K, we have b=Kp.

88
00:14:42.133 --> 00:14:51.967
To solve for p, we can multiply both sides by the inverse of K, call it F, also called the anti-Krylov matrix or decoupling matrix.

89
00:14:51.967 --> 00:15:03.933
Matrix F is also lower-triangular, and looks similar to K, but it is not the same. In fact, F also satisfies similar properties.

90
00:15:03.933 --> 00:15:15.033
Using these properties, we can prove S=KF is the identity matrix I. You can try to prove it if you like.

91
00:15:15.033 --> 00:15:23.600
Hint: S=KF also satisfies the cross even-check rule, that is, it satisfies the relation formula above.

92
00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:35.267
Also note: each row of F matches a polynomial f(n,x), which is the Fibonacci polynomial mentioned in the last video’s “Number of Solutions” part (in OEIS).

93
00:15:35.267 --> 00:15:45.767
Also, the polynomial c(n,x) for matrix C we derived is equal to f(n,x+1) mentioned in that part.

94
00:15:45.767 --> 00:15:54.867
This is not hard to prove: you can get the relation formulas for F and C from their relation, or work backward from the relation formulas.

95
00:15:54.867 --> 00:16:05.167
Also, matrix B(n) can be written in the same form. Here H⊕I is the same as x+1.

96
00:16:05.167 --> 00:16:18.267
Now continue to find p. Since F and K are inverses, we have Fb=FKp=p. Multiply vector b by matrix F, and we get p.

97
00:16:18.267 --> 00:16:32.800
To match the video, because b is written vertically, we write p=Fb. For matrix multiplication, we have P=B''F. Here we omit the transpose symbol.

98
00:16:32.800 --> 00:16:39.967
Write polynomial p(x) in matrix form, call it P.

99
00:16:39.967 --> 00:16:49.400
After we get p=Fb, later computations do not need the full B, only B’s first row, that is vector b.

100
00:16:49.400 --> 00:17:03.033
Because the problem changed from Bx=y to p(H)x=y. So when we build the “generation matrix”, we also only need vector b, that is matrix B'.

101
00:17:03.033 --> 00:17:12.500
Because the formula for b is the same for different n, we can reuse b from n-1 to compute b for n.

102
00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:20.933
So if we start from n=0, we only need O(n) time to get b.

103
00:17:20.933 --> 00:17:32.133
The same is true for computing K and F. Since rows have relation formulas, starting from n=0 also lets us compute them in O(n) time.

104
00:17:32.133 --> 00:17:43.467
If we need a specific n directly, we can optimize to O(n·log(n)) by other methods. This algorithm does not use that, so we won’t expand here.

105
00:17:43.467 --> 00:17:53.333
To get p=Fb, we need vector-matrix multiplication, which usually costs O(n²).

106
00:17:53.333 --> 00:18:02.500
Because F has a relation pattern, in theory we can use FFT and so on to optimize to O(n·log(n)).

107
00:18:02.500 --> 00:18:16.700
On the other hand, when computing p here, we removed the diagonal of B'', that is P=B''F. If we keep the diagonal of B'', then we have C=B'F.

108
00:18:16.700 --> 00:18:32.400
To show this, assume B'F=C', and we get the relation formula above. Since C' and C have the same relation formula, we get C'=C=B'F.

109
00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:44.800
Since C=B'F, we get P=C⊕F. So we can compute C and F, then add them to get P directly, no matrix multiplication needed.

110
00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:58.000
Also, since P=C⊕F, P can be written as a relation formula too, so we can avoid B, C, or F, and derive P directly in O(n) time.

111
00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:08.300
This proof is long, so we do not show it here. If you like, you can prove it from the relation formulas of C and F.

112
00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:21.200
Now we have many ways to get p, and we changed the original problem into p(H)x=y, but what is it good for?

113
00:19:21.200 --> 00:19:33.200
Imagine there is a polynomial q(x) such that q(x)p(x)=1 mod f(x). Here f(x) is the polynomial f(n,x) mentioned earlier.

114
00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:44.233
Then multiply both sides by q(H): we get x=q(H)y. Then we can get x right away.

115
00:19:44.233 --> 00:19:53.467
We call such a polynomial q(x) the inverse polynomial of p(x). So how do we find q(x)?

116
00:19:53.467 --> 00:20:01.167
We can use the extended Euclid algorithm, using f(x) and p(x) to find q(x).

117
00:20:01.167 --> 00:20:13.767
Here we also define a zero polynomial o(x) and a unit polynomial e(x). While operating on f(x) and p(x), we do the same operations on o(x) and e(x).

118
00:20:13.767 --> 00:20:22.367
Like matrix inversion, our goal is: turn f(x) into the zero polynomial, and turn p(x) into the unit polynomial.

119
00:20:22.367 --> 00:20:34.967
We use the subtract-and-shift method: shift p(x) right so its highest term aligns with f(x), then add it to f(x) to cancel f(x)’s highest term.

120
00:20:34.967 --> 00:20:44.567
After adding, if f(x)’s degree is still ≥ p(x)’s degree, keep shifting p(x) right and add it to f(x).

121
00:20:44.567 --> 00:20:58.167
Otherwise, when f(x)’s degree is < p(x)’s degree, swap p(x) and f(x), so f(x)’s degree stays ≥ p(x)’s, and we can keep adding.

122
00:20:58.167 --> 00:21:06.267
Repeat until f(x) becomes zero.

123
00:21:06.267 --> 00:21:17.933
Finally, the remaining p(x) is the gcd of the two polynomials, call it g(x). Also, the remaining e(x) is the inverse of p(x), that is q(x).

124
00:21:17.933 --> 00:21:29.500
Write q(x) as a matrix Q. Note: this Q is not the full inverse matrix Q' from before, but the result of stacking many q(x).

125
00:21:29.500 --> 00:21:38.400
Now we have q(x). Next, by the meaning of q(H)y, we can use it to compute x.

126
00:21:38.400 --> 00:21:49.433
Here we keep multiplying y by H to spread it left and right, then add according to q(x), and we get x.

127
00:21:49.433 --> 00:21:58.467
On the other hand, since q(H) is the inverse matrix Q' of B, and we can prove Q' also satisfies the cross even-check rule.

128
00:21:58.467 --> 00:22:10.800
So we can also compute the first row Q'(0) of Q' by Kq, then use the relation formula to get the full Q', and finally multiply it by y to get x.

129
00:22:10.800 --> 00:22:17.400
The x from these two ways is the same, and you can prove it if you like.

130
00:22:17.400 --> 00:22:28.500
But there is one issue: in the whole process we assumed the inverse polynomial q(x) that satisfies q(x)p(x)=1 mod f(x) exists.

131
00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:38.067
If such q(x) does not exist, what should we do?

132
00:22:38.067 --> 00:22:44.467
In the last video’s “Number of Solutions” part, we mentioned the formula r'(n).

133
00:22:44.467 --> 00:22:54.167
Here gcd means greatest common divisor. It is easy to see gcd(f,c) here is the same g from the extended Euclid algorithm above.

134
00:22:54.167 --> 00:23:02.167
Also, since F=C⊕P, gcd(f,c) and gcd(f,p) are the same.

135
00:23:02.167 --> 00:23:14.167
Here deg means degree, r' is the number of silent moves, that is n-r. r' decides the number of solutions, which is 2^r'.

136
00:23:14.167 --> 00:23:19.700
Write g(x) as a matrix, call it G.

137
00:23:19.700 --> 00:23:31.033
Note that only when matrix B is invertible, we have g(x)=1, and deg(g)=r'=n-r=0.

138
00:23:31.033 --> 00:23:40.333
For example, when n=5, the pseudo-inverse matrix Q' and the identity-like matrix E' after Gaussian elimination look like this.

139
00:23:40.333 --> 00:23:50.933
Here B is not invertible, and its rank is r=3. Now we split the matrix into four blocks using r×r as the border.

140
00:23:50.933 --> 00:24:01.233
1. The top-left r×r block of B is invertible, and it is the inverse of the top-left r×r block of Q'.

141
00:24:01.233 --> 00:24:10.667
2. The bottom-right of Q' and the top-left of E' are identity matrices. The top-right of Q' and the bottom part of E' are zero matrices.

142
00:24:10.667 --> 00:24:24.733
3. The bottom-left Wr of Q' and the top-right silent moves of E' are the same, and equal to (top-left of Q')(top-right of B), or (bottom-left of B)(top-left of Q').

143
00:24:24.733 --> 00:24:35.400
These properties can be derived by block matrix multiplication, together with Gaussian elimination and the symmetry of B. You can prove it if you like.

144
00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:47.033
We can see Q' does not satisfy the cross even-check rule, so we cannot derive it by the relation formula. Also, x computed from Q' first row is not a solution of the original equation.

145
00:24:47.033 --> 00:24:58.333
If we take Q' first row as q(x), and multiply it with p(x), the resulting g(x) is not 1, and its degree is 4.

146
00:24:58.333 --> 00:25:08.367
On the other hand, if we directly use extended Euclid on p(x) and f(x), the resulting g(x) is also not 1.

147
00:25:08.367 --> 00:25:17.767
Multiply the q(x) we got with p(x), we get that g(x), and its degree is 2.

148
00:25:17.767 --> 00:25:25.200
Here we compute q(H)y, and the x we get is still not correct.

149
00:25:25.200 --> 00:25:36.100
The two methods give different q(x) and g(x), both g(x) are not 1, and both q(H)y are not correct solutions.

150
00:25:36.100 --> 00:25:49.167
So if g(x) is not 1, then q(x) does not satisfy q(x)p(x)=1 mod f(x). In other words, such a q(x) does not exist.

151
00:25:49.167 --> 00:25:58.933
So for a non-invertible matrix B, how can we get the correct solution?

152
00:25:58.933 --> 00:26:03.433
In the “First-Row Inverse Method” above, we had these formulas.

153
00:26:03.433 --> 00:26:11.833
Now we define polynomial q'(x) such that q'(x)p(x)=g(x) mod f(x).

154
00:26:11.833 --> 00:26:20.733
Here g(x) is the gcd above, and q'(x) is the q(x) we just got.

155
00:26:20.733 --> 00:26:29.933
Because the x we got before is not correct, we rename it as z, that is z=q'(H)y.

156
00:26:29.933 --> 00:26:39.833
Also, we define the inverse polynomial of q'(x) as p'(x), that is q'(x)p'(x)=1 mod f(x).

157
00:26:39.833 --> 00:26:47.533
It is easy to get these formulas. For simplicity we omit the “mod f(x)” part here.

158
00:26:47.533 --> 00:26:54.333
After整理, we get these formulas.

159
00:26:54.333 --> 00:27:06.433
Finally we get z=g(H)x. Here if g(x)=1, we get the formulas on the right side.

160
00:27:06.433 --> 00:27:18.333
In the extended Euclid part, we already got q'(x) and g(x). So next we only need g(x) and z to get x.

161
00:27:18.333 --> 00:27:29.233
Earlier we had z=q'(H)y. We keep multiplying y by H, then use vector-matrix multiplication to get z.

162
00:27:29.233 --> 00:27:41.333
Now we have z=g(H)x. Since we want x, we cannot solve it with the same method.

163
00:27:41.333 --> 00:27:48.900
This time we need a backward superposition method to get x. Take n=5 as an example.

164
00:27:48.900 --> 00:28:00.900
First, we need to generate g(H) like how we generate matrix B. Call this matrix D. Its rank is the same as matrix B.

165
00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:10.500
1. Create n unit vectors, that is the first row of matrix D. This is the same as matrix B, with n vectors.

166
00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:17.100
2. Use matrix H to spread each first-row vector of D down to later rows.

167
00:28:17.100 --> 00:28:28.133
3. Based on polynomial g(x), add the matching rows of each matrix D. After adding, these rows form a new matrix D.

168
00:28:28.133 --> 00:28:38.033
You can see these steps are like the “First-Row Superposition Method”. We need to generate n matrices, so the time cost is O(n³).

169
00:28:38.033 --> 00:28:47.933
But you can guess: after we swap matrix rows like in the “Matrix Generation Method”, these matrices also satisfy the cross even-check rule.

170
00:28:47.933 --> 00:28:58.133
So we only need to generate the first matrix, then derive the rest, and the time cost drops to O(n²).

171
00:28:58.133 --> 00:29:05.667
In generating the first matrix, each time we multiply a row by H, we get the matrix K we discussed.

172
00:29:05.667 --> 00:29:17.667
So like Q'(0)=Kq, we can just multiply g(x) with K to get the last row of the first matrix, which is the first row d of matrix D.

173
00:29:17.667 --> 00:29:25.367
Then we can use the cross even-check relation to derive the later rows.

174
00:29:25.367 --> 00:29:36.567
Because D is generated from H, it has these properties. Here n=5, r=3, r'=2.

175
00:29:36.567 --> 00:29:44.767
1. For the last r rows, in row n, the leftmost n-r'-1 elements are 0.

176
00:29:44.767 --> 00:29:52.967
2. For the last r rows, in row n, the (n-r')-th element is 1.

177
00:29:52.967 --> 00:30:00.467
3. For the last r rows, any row cannot be made by adding other rows, so they are linearly independent.

178
00:30:00.467 --> 00:30:07.467
4. For the first r' rows, any row can be made by adding the last r rows.

179
00:30:07.467 --> 00:30:15.967
These are not hard to prove, you can prove them if you like.

180
00:30:15.967 --> 00:30:30.433
Now we have z=g(H)x=Dx. We can use D’s properties to solve. Next we need to break z into a superposition of some rows of D, and then we can write x.

181
00:30:30.433 --> 00:30:39.333
Because the last 3 rows of D are independent, we only add rows from the last 3, and ignore the first 2.

182
00:30:39.333 --> 00:30:46.233
Here we try to add some of the last 3 rows onto z, to cancel z out.

183
00:30:46.233 --> 00:30:56.433
Look at the first element of z and the last 3 rows of D. In the last 3 rows, the third row’s first element is 1.

184
00:30:56.433 --> 00:31:07.633
Since z’s first element is already 0, if we add the third row, z’s first element becomes 1, so we cannot add the third row.

185
00:31:07.633 --> 00:31:15.833
Now look at z’s second element. It is 1, so we need to add row 4 to z.

186
00:31:15.833 --> 00:31:23.633
Now z’s second element is canceled, and x’s 4th element is marked as 1.

187
00:31:23.633 --> 00:31:32.833
Next look at z’s third element. Now it became 1, so we need to add row 5 of D.

188
00:31:32.833 --> 00:31:41.133
This time, z is fully canceled to zero, and x’s 5th element is marked as 1.

189
00:31:41.133 --> 00:31:52.633
So we cancel z element by element by adding the last 3 rows of D, and mark the added rows as 1, and we get the final x.

190
00:31:52.633 --> 00:31:57.233
It is easy to see this x is one particular solution.

191
00:31:57.233 --> 00:32:09.133
Since the first r' rows can be written as linear sums of the last r rows, before canceling z, we can first add z with any of the first r' rows, then solve.

192
00:32:09.133 --> 00:32:17.333
Since there are 2^r' choices for the first r' rows, the number of solutions is also 2^r'.

193
00:32:17.333 --> 00:32:27.133
On the other hand, because D satisfies the cross even-check rule, it is highly symmetric. The row and column coordinates can be swapped.

194
00:32:27.133 --> 00:32:39.100
So we can also add only the first r rows and cancel from right to left. Since the result is the same, we omit it here.

195
00:32:39.100 --> 00:32:45.000
Careful viewers may find these two formulas have the same shape.

196
00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:57.067
Since we can solve x from the first formula by backward superposition, why can’t we use the same method to solve x from the second formula?

197
00:32:57.067 --> 00:33:06.967
Because D is made from g(H). It has a banded upper-triangular back-substitution structure, and it satisfies the four properties above.

198
00:33:06.967 --> 00:33:18.667
But B=p'(H)D breaks this structure, so it does not satisfy these properties. Here D=g(H) is not invertible, so p'(H) is not unique.

199
00:33:18.667 --> 00:33:27.567
However, when g=1, this method works, although it first needs the full matrix B.

200
00:33:27.567 --> 00:33:39.067
Also, because B is not triangular, we must mark where each row’s first 1 is, to choose rows. So directly computing q(H)y is easier.

201
00:33:39.067 --> 00:34:11.433
In the end, we solved Bx=y using the Euclid method and backward superposition, and made an O(n²) algorithm for Lights Out.

202
00:34:11.433 --> 00:34:18.033
Above is a summary of the O(n²) algorithm.

203
00:34:18.033 --> 00:34:32.233
Vector-matrix multiplication, the Euclid algorithm, and backward elimination can, in theory, be improved to O(n·log(n)) using convolution, FFT, or Newton iteration.

204
00:34:32.233 --> 00:34:45.833
But since the uploader is weak in “Signals and Systems”, “Digital Signal Processing”, “Numerical Analysis”, we won’t study it now. If you are interested, you can study it and leave comments.

205
00:34:45.833 --> 00:35:19.000
